[[File:Laura Wheeler Waring.jpg|thumb|Laura Wheeler Waring]]
'''Laura Wheeler Waring''' (May 16, 1887 &ndash; February 3, 1948) was an [[African-American]] artist and educator, best known for her paintings of prominent African Americans produced during the [[Harlem Renaissance]].  
{{TOC right}}

==Life and career==
Laura Wheeler was born May 16, 1887 in [[Hartford, Connecticut]], the fourth child of six born to Mary and Reverend Robert Foster Wheeler; she graduated from [[Hartford Public High School]] in 1906 and studied at the [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]],<ref name="bporg"/> graduating in 1914.<ref name="wnet"/>

Waring worked at [[Cheyney State Teachers College|Cheyney Training School for Teachers]] in Philadelphia, establishing art and music programs, which she directed for more than thirty years.<ref name="bporg"/>

Her paintings began to draw attention during a 1924 European trip in which she was accompanied by novelist [[Jessie Redmon Fauset]];<ref name="bporg"/> Back home, Waring was among the artists displayed in the country's first art exhibition dedicated to African-American art, held in 1927 by the [[William E. Harmon Foundation]].<ref name="wnet"/> Her work was soon displayed in American galleries including the [[Corcoran Gallery]] and museums such as the [[Brooklyn Museum]] and the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]].<ref name="bporg"/>

Laura Wheeler married Walter E. Waring, a [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)|Lincoln University]] professor, in 1927.<ref name="bporg"/>

She died on February 3, 1948, in her Philadelphia home after a long illness.<ref name="bporg"/>

